children.subject: +1, taking stat 134 alongside cs 70 is overkill (i.e. there will be significant amount of overlap). Also CS70, along with EE 16A/B will be more than enough prep for Math 110.
To avoid this overlap, what upper-div probability course would you recommend if a student wants to further explore the field? EECS 126? STAT 140 (which is pretty similar to 134 tbh)?

IMO, the mathematical intuition you'll learn in CS70 is more valuable for MATH110. If you already took EE16A then you'll be fine. However, STAT134 is an upper-div stats class with fairly abstract material. The department highly recommends you take MATH110 as your first upper-div in order to settle in well. I wouldn't recommend taking it concurrently with CS70 since that is also a difficult course.

history.content:
EE16AB + CS70 is a perfect background for taking Math 110. Conversations with faculty in the math department have confirmed this. You will be have intuition about n-dimensional real and complex spaces, as well as linear maps, Euclidean inner products, changes of coordinates, and Eigenstructure from the 16 series. You will be ready for nontrivial proofs from 70, as well as have more of a feeling that fields exist besides R and C. This will put you in a position to connect to the more axiomatic and abstract perspective on linear algebra covered in Math 110. 

In terms of probability courses, it is consensus that students who have taken 70 and understood what is going on should plan on taking 126 after 70.
